nses to the multifaceted urban culture of Berlin in the 1920s and 1930s.Examining a variety of media ranging from scientific writings to literature and the visual arts, the authors trace gendered discourses as they developed to make sense of and regulate emerging new images of femininity. Besides treating classic films such as Metropolis and Berlin: Symphony of a Great City, the articles discuss other forms of mass culture, including the fashion industry and the revue performances of Josephine Baker. Their emphasis on women's critical involvement in the construction of their own modernity illustrates the significance of the Weimar cultural experience and its relevance to contemporary gender, German, film, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminismxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aFeminismzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban womenxHistoryxGermany. 0aUrban womenzGermanyxHistory. 0aWomenxHistoryx20th centuryxGermany. 0aWomenzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aartistic and social movements.  acomprehensive.  aforms of mass culture.  aliterature and visual arts.  amodernism and urbanization in weimar germany.  anineteen twenties and thirties.  apolitical movements.  ascientific writings.  aurban culture of berlin.  awomen as active participants.  awomens experience.  awomens involvement in constructing modernity.1 aAnkum, Katharina von, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrame, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGleber, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHake, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Beth Irwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/